Nikolai Makarov completed his project in the theory of random normal matrices (RNM), Laplacian growth, and Schwarz reflections supported by the NSF grant DMS-1500821. During the funding period, the research was focused on the problems of convergence of various natural point processes arising in the RNM model, as well as on several related fundamental open problems in classical complex analysis and logarithmic potential theory.
The PI achieved the main goals of the project and made significant progress in the following directions:
(i) convergence of the rescaled RNM point processes at regular and singular boundary points of the droplet (support of the equilibrium measure);
(ii)  topology of algebraic droplets and applications to the inverse problem of potential theory;
(iii) inverse spectral problem for canonical systems, applications to uncertainty principle;
(iv) univalent polynomials: extremal polynomials and their classifications in terms of Hubbard trees; 
(v)  the dynamics of the Schwarz reflections: the corresponding Julia-type and Mandelbrot-type sets;
(vi) calculus of conformal fields on Riemann surfaces
These results are presented in twelve full length papers (published or submitted for publication).
The results and methods of the project have made an impact on several areas of analysis and mathematical physics: random normal matrices, potential theory, inverse problems, univalent functions, and complex dynamics.  Also, some results and ideas of the project should be of interest to theoretical physicists working in conformal field theory, quantum Hall effect, non-equilibrium growth phenomena, and disordered systems.
The project provided research and training opportunities for several graduate students and postdocs. The PI developed and taught three new graduate courses at Caltech: "Calculus of conformal fields on compact Riemann surfaces", "Inverse spectral problem for canonical systems", and "Random normal matrix model".  In addition, he helped organize two conferences on related topics.



